            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Maya Miller\u2019s palate was shaped by a duality. Raised in Marin County, she was the daughter of a pragmatic Korean immigrant mother, a nurse who expressed love through meticulously crafted, flavorful meals, and a Caucasian-American father, an architect who taught her to appreciate structure, landscape, and unspoken history. Her childhood was a blend of kimchi-making workshops and discussions about building aesthetics, instilling in her an appreciation for both tradition and form.\n\nInitially pursuing a practical business degree at UC Davis, Maya\u2019s life pivoted during a semester abroad in Lyon, France. It wasn't just the wine; it was the culture surrounding it\u2014the way a single bottle could encapsulate a region's history, soil, and the life's work of a family. This was the structure and story her father taught her, but in liquid form. Upon returning, she decisively switched her focus, eventually earning a Master's in Hospitality Management.\n\nHer career began with grit, not glamour. She worked as a server, then a sommelier\u2019s assistant in a bustling Financial District restaurant, absorbing every lesson she could. Her big break came when she was hired as the Sommelier, and eventually promoted to Wine Director, for an acclaimed contemporary restaurant in Hayes Valley. The role is a perfect synthesis of her skills: managing a six-figure inventory, training staff, and, her favorite part, guiding diners on the floor, translating complex vintages into accessible stories.\n\nMaya\u2019s life is defined by her 0.8-mile radius. She lives in a modern apartment just a few blocks from work, a walking commute she considers a cherished urban luxury. Her days are a sensory symphony\u2014mornings spent tasting with distributors, afternoons refining her wine list, and evenings orchestrating service. Her social circle is a tight-knit group of industry friends\u2014chefs, bartenders, and fellow sommeliers who understand the unique pressures and passions of their world.\n\nNow at 27, Maya feels a deep connection to San Francisco's dynamic culinary scene. Her dream is no longer just to manage a cellar, but to own one. She envisions a small, intimate wine bar in her neighborhood, a space that reflects her own story: blending Old World reverence with bright, Californian innovation."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe recalls sitting at the heavy oak table in their Marin kitchen, age ten. The air was a mix of her mother\u2019s pungent, spicy gochugaru paste and the faint, dusty graphite from her father\u2019s architectural sketches. He was drawing a clean, modern guest house while her mother\u2019s hands, firm and knowing, packed kimchi into glass jars. In that moment, she learned that structure and sustenance were not opposites, but two languages of love. This duality became the foundation of her worldview, shaping her ability to find the art in pragmatism.\n\n2.\nAt twenty, standing in a damp, chilly cellar in Beaujolais, she watched a third-generation vigneron with soil-caked hands pour her a glass of Morgon. He didn\u2019t just pour; he offered a story of granite, struggle, and his grandfather\u2019s belief in the Gamay grape. The wine tasted of history. It was the moment the abstract concepts her father taught her\u2014landscape, structure, story\u2014became tangible and alive on her palate. This experience irrevocably shifted her life\u2019s ambition from business spreadsheets to the stories held within bottles.\n\n3.\nIt was 1 AM in the Financial District restaurant, age 23. Her arms ached from polishing hundreds of Riedel stems, the city lights a distant, blurry promise outside. She was just an assistant, exhausted and invisible. But as she lined up the gleaming glasses, she saw the head sommelier\u2019s cryptic tasting notes left on the bar. Instead of fatigue, a quiet, fierce resolve ignited within her. She would learn that language. This moment forged her grit, teaching her that expertise is built in the unglamorous, lonely hours.\n\n4.\nLast year, at her post in Hayes Valley, a young couple stared, intimidated, at her extensive wine list. Seeing their anxiety, Maya approached not as a director, but as a guide. She spoke of a small producer from the Loire Valley, an underdog story of minerality and citrus. When they tasted it, their faces lit up with understanding and delight. That feeling\u2014of translating a complex world into a moment of shared, simple joy\u2014was the purest form of success she had ever known. It affirmed that her true talent was in connection.\n\n5.\nJust last month, walking home through the hazy evening fog, listening to jazz on her headphones. She passed a small, dark storefront on a quiet side street, a \"For Lease\" sign taped inside the window. It was just a space, but in that instant, she could see it all: the warm lighting, the clink of glasses, the exact shade of blue for the walls. The abstract dream of her own wine bar suddenly had a physical address. It was a jolt of terrifying, exhilarating clarity, transforming her ambition into a tangible goal."
